5|$|The broad {{heading of}} {{illegality}} may {{be divided into}} two sub-headings. In the first case, the High Court inquires into whether the <b>public</b> <b>authority</b> was empowered to take a particular course of action or make a decision, and, in the other, whether it exercised its discretion wrongly even though it was empowered to act. Where the Court finds that the <b>public</b> <b>authority</b> had exceeded its jurisdiction or had exercised its discretion wrongly, it may invalidate the act or decision.|$|E
5|$|The broad {{heading of}} {{judicial}} review of illegality may {{be divided into two}} sub-headings. In the first case, the High Court inquires into whether the <b>public</b> <b>authority</b> was empowered to take a particular course of action or make a decision, and, in the other, whether it exercised its discretion wrongly even though it was empowered to act. Where the Court finds that the <b>public</b> <b>authority</b> had exceeded its jurisdiction or had exercised its discretion wrongly, it may strike down the decision on the basis of illegality.|$|E
